@Node Intro "Introduction"
@Next Reqs

INTRODUCTION

    This program implements a new kind of scope, a "wrapped monoscope".
    Most modules look much better with a wrapped monoscope than they do
    with the traditional one (the double mode in Delitracker's monoscope, or
    the Spacescope in Eagleplayer). The Ravescope also has this "traditonal"
    mode, as well as a new "alternative" mode.


@Endnode
@Node Reqs "Requirements"
@Next Interaction

REQUIREMENTS

    OS 3.x
    68020 or better
    2MB fastmem
    Reqtools.library
    Hippoplayer by K-P Koljonen or
    Delitracker by Peter Kunath and Frank Riffel or
    Eagleplayer by Henryk Richter and Jan Blumenthal


@Endnode
@Node Interaction "The Ravescope and its module players"
@Next UsingIt


                  USING THE RAVESCOPE WITH EXTERNAL PLAYERS

                @{" Overview    " Link UsingIt } General info about the Ravescope
                @{" Hippoplayer " Link WithHip } Using the Ravescope with HiP
                @{" Delitracker " Link WithDT  } Using it with Delitracker
                @{" Eagleplayer " Link WithEP  } Using it with Eagleplayer

                If you want to adapt the Ravescope to your own
                          player, then click @{" here " Link Programming}.

@Endnode
@Node UsingIt "How the Ravescope communicates with module players"
@Next WithHip

    When the Ravescope is running, it can be in one of three modes:

    PLY_NONE    Nothing is happening. 10 times a second it will look to see if
                Hippoplayer is present.

    PLY_HIP     The Ravescope is using Hippoplayer.

    PLY_HOST    The Ravescope is using a host. A host is a separate process
                whose job is to fill out a set of channel structures,
                describing the sound that is currently being played. I
                implemented the host concept to make it easier to write new
                "drivers" for other module players. At present only two hosts
                have been written, one for Delitracker and one for
                Eagleplayer. Delitracker considers its host to be a genie,
                while the Ravescope simply sees it as its current host. In
                the same way, Eagleplayer sees an engine where the Ravescope
                sees a host. Enough of this... The names are not really
                important, they are just different kinds of plugins. I can't
                even remember why I elected to call my flavour hosts. Well, I
                couldn't call them engines or genies, that would have meant
                the end of my neutrality. And plugin/driver sounded too
                general to refer to. So, ehrm, I adopted my own name.

    When the Ravescope is started it will search for any recognized players
    and grab the one that is playing. If none is playing it will grab the
    first host it can find. If none is present it will simply wait until
    something happens. The player that is playing will always have the scope's
    attention.

    Every time the Ravescope grabs a player, it will try to load and parse
    this player's configuration file.

    When you quit the host that is currently being used by the Ravescope,
    the Ravescope will quit too if the host's quit=kill flag is set. Here's
    a summary of all the host specific flags:

    POPUP       When checked the RaveScope will be started as soon as
                Delitracker/Eagleplayer has been loaded.

    ACTIVATE    The RaveScope window will be activated when started.

    QUIT=KILL   When the Ravescope's current host is removed (which will
                happen, for instance, when the player quits) the RaveScope
                will be 'killed' as well.

@Endnode
@Node WithHip "Using the RaveScope with Hippoplayer"
@Next WithDT

USING THE RAVESCOPE WITH HIPPOPLAYER

    You will have to start both Hippoplayer and the Ravescope. Once you have a
    module playing, the Ravescope will begin to display it.

    The configuration file will always be referred to as s:HippoPlayer.rave.

    Not all types of module formats can be displayed by Hippoplayer, Octamed
    modules for example. Modules with more than 4 channels will be mixed into
    2 channels which are then displayed.

    The Ravescope's "Popup", "Activate" and "Quit=Kill" menu items have no
    meaning or effect with hippoplayer (yet).

@Endnode
@Node WithDT "Using the RaveScope with Delitracker"
@Next WithEP

USING THE RAVESCOPE WITH DELITRACKER

    Start delitracker and open up the genie window. Click on 'add' and select
    the supplied RaveScope @{b}genie@{ub}. A filerequester should now pop up asking
    you for the location of the Ravescope @{b}executable@{ub} (the main program). The
    genie will then attempt to launch the file you have selected, and if
    there are no problems you should soon see the Ravescope window. Adjust its
    position and size, then select 'save settings' in the Ravescope menu. The
    next time you start the Ravescope through Delitracker, you will not have
    to specify the path to the executable again.
    
    Pressing 'hide' in the genie window will quit the RaveScope. Pressing
    'show' will start it again.

    When the Ravescope is used with Delitracker, all channels will be
    displayed separately. So a 16 channel fasttracker module may show 16
    waveforms at once. This doesn't always look too good.

    The path to the delitracker ravescope configuration file is
    $DELICONFIG/RaveScope.prefs. That is, Delitracker stores all configuration
    files in a directory specified in the environmental variable DELICONFIG.

@Endnode
@Node WithEP "Using the RaveScope with Eagleplayer"
@Next KeybCtrl

USING THE RAVESCOPE WITH EAGLEPLAYER

    Start Eagleplayer and select 'Load Engine' in the engine menu, or 'add'
    from the manager, or if it's in your engine directory, just click on its
    name in the engine menu. When the engine has been added a filerequester
    should pop up, asking you for the location of the Ravescope @{b}executable@{ub}
    (the main program). The engine will then try to launch the file you have
    selected, and if there are no problems you should soon see the Ravescope's
    window. Adjust its position, sizes and settings to your liking and select
    'save settings' in the RaveScope menu, or Eagleplayer's menu. (Everytime
    you save Eagleplayer's configuration, the ravescope's config will be saved
    too @{i}if the Ravescope is present and has grabbed eagleplayer.@{ui} The next time
    you start the Ravescope through eagleplayer, you won't need to specify the
    path again.

    The config-file will be saved to the directory where Eagleplayer stores
    its configuration files under the name RaveScope.cfg.

    The Ravescope will always display 4 channels when used with Eagleplayer.
    Modules with more channels will be displayed as a 4 channel mix.

    For some reasone mp3 modules looks very bad when played with Eagleplayer.

@Endnode
@Node KeybCtrl "Keyboard control"
@Next MenuCtrl

KEYBOARD CONTROL

    The menu cannot be used when in fullscreen mode, but you can still control
    the display with the keyboard.

    KEY, NO QUALIFIER

        W - Wrapped mode on/off

        T - Traditional mode on/off

        A - Alternative mode on/off

        I - Invert background on/off

        S - Strobo mode on/off

        Q - (or Escape) - Quit

        F - Switch between fullscreen and window mode

    To change the various scope-mode's accuracies, use the numerical keypad.
    The keys 7, 8 and 9 will increase the wrapped, traditional and alternative
    accuracy. The corresponding key below, 4, 5 or 6 will decrease it.

    To increase/decrease the dark part (unless you have invert switched on) in
    the strobo mode, press shift + 7/4. Use 8/5 to control the bright part.


    RIGHT AMIGA + KEY

	I - Iconify

        S - Save config

	F - Go fullscreen in a new screenmode

@Endnode
@Node MenuCtrl "Menu control"
@Next Limitations

MENU FUNCTIONS AND SHORTCUTS

    PROJECT MENU

        Quit (shortcut: right Amiga+q or just q)

        Iconify (shortcut: right Amiga+i)

        Set screenmode (shortcut: right Amiga+f)
        Opens a screenmode requester and opens a screen in the selected mode.


    SETTINGS MENU

        Popup
        Pop up the RaveScope when the player starts?

        Activate
        Activate the display window when the RaveScope is started?

        Quit=Kill
        Quit the RaveScope when the player exits?

        Colours
        When this item is checked, the next time the RaveScope is opened in
        fullscreen mode, it will be in a 256 colour screen. This is @{b}very@{ub} slow.
        @{i}It is not yet possible to have colours when in window mode.@{ui}

        Invert (shortcut: I)
        Replace the background colour with foreground.

        Strobo
        Flash the display. Change the interval with numeric keypad 7/8/4/5 and
        shift.

        Fullscreen (shortcut: f)
        When selected will switch between window and fullscreen mode. When
        going into fullscreen mode, the last used screenmode will be selected.

        Save settings (shortcut: right Amiga+s)
        The RaveScope will save the settings to the configuration file that is
        associated with the current player in use.

        Reset to defaults
        Open in a window with default settings.

@Endnode
@Node Limitations "Limitations"
@Next Memory

LIMITATIONS

    GFX CARDS

    I still haven't got a graphics card, and I've had no request for better
    support for gfx cards in the display. So I haven't done anything about
    this yet.


    MP3'S IN EAGLEPLAYER

    For some reason the waveforms Eagleplayer gives me when playing mp3's
    looks like complete crap. And it seems 4 channels are displayed, where
    only two should be.

@Endnode
@Node Memory "Memory usage"
@Next Speed

MEMORY USAGE

    I first made this scope on an A500, and using large look-up tables was the
    only way to make it fast enough. Now, as I have an 060, I'm not so sure
    anymore if this can still be justified. The memory needed for the main table
    are circumference * (higest of width/height) * 2 bytes. The default display
    of 280 * 160 thus requires (280*2 + 160*2) * 280 * 2 = 0.5MB. A super-hires
    interlaced display of 1400x560 pixels needs almost 11MB. I will make a
    realtime version and see how it goes...

@Endnode
@Node Speed "Speed"
@Next Hints

SPEED

    The init/display routines are made in asm, the rest in C. Half a frame
    (average) is lost in syncing with the VBL (WaitTOF(); BltBitMap();).
    I may improve this in the next version.
    The clearing and display are not optimised at all yet.
    There's a frame-counter in the top of the mousepointer. The number of
    dots indicate how many frames it took to draw the last display.

    The inner-loop, for those who are interested, looks like this:

	Loop:	move.b	(a0)+,d0
		move.w	(a1,d0.w*2),d1
		move.l	(a2,d1.w*4),d1
		bfset	(a4){d1:1}
		adda.w	a3,a2
		dbra	d6,Loop

    The bfset instruction take (if I remember correctly) at least 20 cycles,
    even on a 060. When I used a display with less than 64k pixels I was able
    to halve the precalc data thanks to this instruction, without losing (or
    gaining) any speed on the 020 I used at the time. So this is why it has
    stuck with me...

@Endnode
@Node Hints "Hints and warnings"
@Next Background

HINTS/WARNINGS

    * 100% usually looks the best for protracker modules. PS3M's or mp3's may
      look better with 200% because they only output 2 channels. Do not
      set the wrapped accuracy higher than this, it won't look good because
      (I think) often the sample frequency isn't high enough.

    * PS3M's look much better with a high volume-boost and the main-volume
      set to maximum in Hippoplayer.

    * DeliTracker gives the same data regardless of the sample-boost, but
      the volume must be set to maximum.

    * Resizing is very slow because each time the size change, all the look-up
      tables must be recalculated.

    ! Do not waste your life looking at this scope, as I have done!


@Endnode
@Node Background "Background"
@Next History

BACKGROUND

    4-5 years ago I saw a monoscope for the first time. (It was the
    Quadraplayer's I think.)  When, some months later, I tried to make my
    own (not having any idea of how it was done) I accidently invented this
    "wrapped" scopemode, and to my delight it looked even better.

    I released a first version of it in a music disk-mag I was coding at
    the time, Subculture. (The editor has now turned over to the dark side,
    so there will probably not be a new issue.) There I explained how to do
    it, hoping the scope would spread to my favourite module players. But it
    didn't, either because no one saw it, or because it's a bit complicated
    to implement. (It's not just a question of modifying the inner loop,
    like when converting a plain scope to a monoscope.)


@Endnode
@Node History "History"
@Next Future

HISTORY

    v1.0 (980209)

        ** The first release.

        BUGS: I seem to have removed all bugs. Since I tracked down the last
        one, two weeks ago, I've had NO strange crashes or things like that.
        Possibly the error-handling contains flaws, I haven't tried
        everything.


    v1.1 (980315)

        ** Added support for DeliTracker through the DeliRave genie.

        (I contacted Peter Kunath, author of Delitracker, asking him for more
        information about how to make a genie. He immediately sent me the
        source to his monoscope (which was just what I needed) and has been
        very helpful ever since).

        ** Added the keyword 'DELICONFIG' so that you can use DeliRave's
           config settings with HippoPlayer as well.

        ** The wrapped mode has been prepared for use with 16 bit samples.
           Neither Hippoplayer nor Delitracker gives their userprograms more
           than 8 bits though, so this is quite pointless at the moment.

        ** Added a simple strobo-mode. This looks quite awful, but I seem to
           remember that this can be fun when the room is dark and you're
           drunk.

        ** Remembered to turn on compiler optimizations this time.

        BUGS: It is still very stable, much to my surprise. MPEGA player
        did occasionally give enforcer hits, and I felt a bit guilty for this
        because it has only happened when DeliRave has been active. (But on
        the other hand, I only run enforcer when running DeliRave...)
        Sometimes when a new module is loaded, it won't load until the
        ravewindow is activated. I haven't looked into this yet.


    v1.2 (980922)

        ** Restructured the whole program to make it easier to add support for
           more players. This turned out to be very complicated and took me
           several months.

        ** Rewrote the Delitracker genie to work with this new concept.

        ** Added Eagleplayer support.

        ** I accidently had two WaitTOF:s (wait until next frame) per display.
           Removed one of them.

        ** Got rid of strange flickering, both in window and fullscreen mode.

        ** Added a menu.

	** Changed and added a few keyboard/menu shortcuts.

        ** There's now a special configuration file that will be loaded when
           the RaveScope is using Hippoplayer.

        ** Scrapped all commandline arguments. They were not needed since
           all players are now associated with a configuration file.

        ** The RaveScope can now be iconified. If it is, and a new RaveScope
           is started, this will deiconify the old one.

        ** When a RaveScope player starts to play it will automatically try to
           grab the RaveScope.

        ** Added colours for the fullscreen modes.

        ** Switched from text documentation to amigaguide and added an
           installer script.

        BUGS: Still very stable, though deadlocks can perhaps occur. There's
        a few minor flaws. No double buffering in colour mode for instance.

@Endnode
@Node Future "Future"
@Next Programming

THE FUTURE

    I'd like to add support for more players.

    When (at last!) seeing my favourite OctaMED modules in a wrapped scope,
    it was somewhat disappointing. They are made by Orpheus (into persona,
    emerald dreams, your underworld etc... anyone know where to get his
    latest modules?) and all modules seem to contain a special sample that
    when displayed just looks like crap. So I am going to add masking, which
    will split the screen into one display for each channel so that those
    channels that don't look good can be disabled.

    The following features has been requested, and will probably be
    implemented sooner or later (but I don't know in what order) :

    ** One colour for each channel, or as many as the current screenmode
       allows. This would make it much slower of course, but perhaps it would
       be worth it.

    ** Connect the dots with lines. Same thing here.

    ** Wrap the scope around a circle instead of a rectangle. Would not take
       more time, but the display size would be limited.

    ** More display modes.

    Going PPC would be nice, but I don't think I can afford to buy one before
    the new Amiga comes out. This does not illustrate how expensive a PPC
    card is, but rather how poor I am :(

@Endnode
@Node Programming "Developer information"
@Next Thanks

CONNECTING THE RAVESCOPE TO YOUR OWN PLAYER

    This is quite easy. All functions to grab and handle the RaveScope can be
    obtained by assembling hostfuncs.s.

    Basically, you need to have a task fill in a set of channel structures
    and then signal the RaveScope that these structures are now ready to be
    displayed.

    THE HOST'S PERSPECTIVE (A host is the genie/engine/userprogram)

        All things that the ravehosts need to do that concerns the RaveScope
        should be done by calling a routine in the HostFuncs object file. This
        routine may reside in the Ravescope executable, but the host need not
        worry about that.

    USING THE RAVESCOPE

        Call the internal routine called rh_InitHost. This routine will try to
        launch the RaveScope if your popup flag is set. (If your configuration
        file does not contain a valid path to the ravescope, a filerequester
        will be called.) Example:

	Begin	lea	"MyPlayer",a0		;Name of your player
		lea	"Config/Rave.cfg",a1 	;Path to your config-file
		sub.l	a5,a5			;Please allocate the RaveHost
						;structure for me
		sub.l	a2,a2			;No tags!
		jsr	_rh_InitHost		;Init it...
		beq	.Error			;Serious error, quit and
						;report failure...
						;Else: a5 now points to the
						;RaveHost structure

        The rh_InitHost routine will return GT (d0=1) if the RaveScope has
        been grabbed, and MI (d0=-1) if it has not been grabbed.  But you
        don't need to act on this.  If the user has cleared the ravescope
        popup flag, it means he wants to start the RaveScope manually from the
        shell/wb.  When this is done the RaveScope will notify you.  So Enter
        your mainloop, where you want to update the channel-structures for the
        RaveScope to display.  Wait() on your player's (eagleplayer,
        delitracker) message port, and the RaveHost's messageport (allocated
        in rh_InitHost) and process the messages.  If you get a message/signal
        from your player that the player's channel structures have been
        updated, then check if you have the RaveScope.  If you do, you must
        update the RaveScope's channel-structures too.

        Here's an example where your player is assumed to have created a
        subprocess responsible for the communication with the RaveScope.  A
        signal number has been allocated, which your player uses to signal
        your subprocess when the channel structures have changed, i.e that
        it's time for the RaveScope to produce a new display.

		move.b	UpdateBit,d4		;Bit to signal change in
						;channel structures
		move.b	MP_SIGBIT(a5),d5	;Get the Ravehost's msgport
						;signal bit number

	.Main	moveq	#0,d0			;Go to sleep until we get a
		bset	d4,d0			;message from the RaveScope or
		bset	d5,d0			;your player.
		CALLEXE	Wait
		move.l	d0,d3			;Remember signal mask in d3

		btst	d5,d3			;Got a msg from the Ravescope?
		beq	.NoRM			;No...
		jsr	_rh_ProcMsgs		;Yes, handle it.
		beq	.Exit			;The RaveScope is quitting. We
						;choose to quit too (not
						;necessary, it may come back)
	.NoRM	btst	d4,d3			;Got a signal from your player?
		beq	.Main			;No...
		lea	UpdateChans,a2		;Yes, a2=address to your
						;routine to update channels
		moveq	#4,d1			;Make room for no more than 4
						;channels
		jsr	_rh_UpdateChans		;Update the channel structs
						;This routine will amongst
						;other things jsr (a2)
		tst.b	QuitFlag		;Check your player's quitflag
		bne	.Main			;and loop back if it isn't set

        Finally, when you quit, all you have to do is call the rh_FreeHost
        routine.  It will free everything allocated in the rh_InitHost
        routine, including the rh_RaveHost structure if you specified NULL for
        this in the rh_InitHost call (forcing that routine to allocate it).
        If you have the RaveScope when exiting, rh_FreeHost will send a
        message to the RaveScope, informing it that we are quitting.  The
        Ravescope will quit too, if your rh_oQuitEqKill flag is set.  Example:

	.Exit	jsr	rh_FreeHost		;Free everything
		moveq	#1,d0			;Signal success
		rts

	.Error	moveq	#0,d0			;You don't have to call
		rts				;rh_FreeHost if rh_InitHost
                                                ;failed.

        This example is a bit simplified, but hopefully you'll get the idea.
        For more details, look in the supplied example sources that I used to
        implement eagleplayer/delitracker support, or check the hostfuncs
        source in the same directory.

    If you are interested there are some example sources in the developer dir.
    Don't hesitate to @{"contact me" Link Contact} if you need help.

